T1  - Is the business cycle characterized by deterministic chaos?
AU  - Brock, William A
AU  - Sayers, Chera L
JO  - Journal of Monetary Economics
VL  - 22
IS  - 1
SP  - 71
EP  - 90
PY  - 1988
DA  - 1988/07/01/
SN  - 0304-3932
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-3932(88)90170-5
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304393288901705
AB  - Tests are conducted on U.S. macroeconomic data for the presence of low-dimensional deterministic chaos, where ‘deterministic chaos’ is defined as in Grandmont's (1985) Walras-Bowley lecture or in Brock (1986). The idea is to test for evidence of endogenous instability causing the business cycle. Low-order autoregressions are hard to reject with our methods. Evidence of chaos is weak but our tests may be too weak to detect it. Evidence of nonlinearity is present in employment 1950-I to 1983-IV, unemployment 1949-I to 1982-IV, monthly post-war industrial production, and pig iron production 1877–1937.
